    <h2>Frequently Asked Questions</h2>

    <h3>What is the transformer architecture and why did it change AI?</h3>
    <p>The transformer (introduced in "Attention Is All You Need," 2017) replaced recurrent networks with a mechanism called self-attention that processes all tokens in a sequence simultaneously rather than one at a time. This enabled massive parallelization during training, which unlocked scaling to the model sizes needed for GPT-3, Claude, Gemini, and every major LLM that followed.</p>

    <h3>What is "attention" in plain English?</h3>
    <p>Attention is a mechanism that allows each word in a sentence to consider every other word when deciding what it means. For "The bank by the river flooded," the word "bank" attends strongly to "river" to resolve the ambiguity. The model learns which relationships matter most — this is what makes transformers far better at understanding context than earlier approaches.</p>

    <h3>Why does context window size matter for practical applications?</h3>
    <p>The context window limits how much text the model can "see" at once — documents, conversation history, retrieved chunks. A 4K-token window (early GPT-3.5) can handle a few pages; a 1M-token window (Gemini 2.5 Pro) can handle an entire codebase. Applications like document Q&amp;A, long-form code generation, and multi-turn enterprise workflows require larger windows. See <a href={`${base}/chapters/08-rag`}>Chapter 8 on RAG</a> for strategies when content exceeds window limits.</p>

    <h3>How do GPT, Claude, and Gemini relate to the transformer architecture?</h3>
    <p>All modern LLMs are transformer variants — specifically decoder-only transformers pre-trained to predict the next token. GPT, Claude, Gemini, Llama, and Mistral all share this foundation but differ in training data, scale, alignment techniques, and architectural refinements. Understanding the base architecture helps you evaluate vendor claims and anticipate capability limits.</p>

    <h3>What is the difference between encoder-only, decoder-only, and encoder-decoder transformers?</h3>
    <p>Encoder-only models (BERT, RoBERTa) read text in both directions and are best for classification and retrieval. Decoder-only models (GPT, Claude, Llama) generate text left-to-right and power LLM chat. Encoder-decoder models (T5, BART) encode input then decode output — suited for translation and summarization. Most current chat LLMs are decoder-only.</p>

